HUB Roadmap Library Transmission, Reproductive Numbers

.

How do we compute \(R_C\) in places where transmission is seasonal? The problem for computing an average is that the expected number of cases per case is different depending on when in the year a case was acquired. At the end of the transmission season, most of the infectious days will occur in the trough. The answer to this question involves computing the lead eigenvalue and its associated eigenvector for the next generation operator. Here, we illustrate the concepts by constructing examples.

Seasonality

We have to be clear on what we mean by seasonality. One way to do this is to specify a daily varying vectorial capacity how many infectious bites would eventually arise from all the mosquitoes feeding on this one human each day of the year? For purposes of this exercise, we will construct these objects assuming seasonality in VC is driven exclusively by seasonality in mosquito densities.

The first step in our algorithm is thus to specify the seasonal pattern in mosquito densities. We will constrain this mathematical object so that we can set the mean intensity of transmission to any value we want. We thus modify it to have an arithmetic mean of one, when averaged over a year. For convenience, the following function constructs several different function families, ftMozy, that implement families:

ftMozy = function(t, par){
  UseMethod("ftMozy", par)
}

Trig

A generalized sinusoidal family of functions:

\[ M(t) = M \max(0, (1 + a + b \sin(2 \pi (t-s))^p) \]

Block

A two paramter family of functions, called block2. \[ M(t) = \begin{array}{rl} a & \mbox{if} (t-s) \mod 365 > v\\ b & \mbox{if} (t-s) < v \end{array} \]

The Next Generation

Tmh

\[\begin{equation} {\cal T}_{M\rightarrow H}(t) = \begin{array}{cl} 0 & \mbox{if } t<t_0 + \tau\\ \frac{fq}{g} e^{-g(t-t_0-\tau)} &\mbox{if } t>t_0 + \tau \end{array} \end{equation}\]

To compute the next generation for the temporal operator, we have to be very specific about when the infectious bites occur. VC only describes bites arising, but under the standard model, it is possible to write out a formula describing when they would be expected to occur. Here, we start counting after a mosquito has become infected:

makeTmh = function(EIP=12, p=.9, fq=.3, tol = 0.001, plot=FALSE){
  Vtime = p^c(1:365) 
  Vtime[1:(EIP-1)] = 0 
  Vtime = fq*Vtime
  cs = cumsum(Vtime)
  Vtime = Vtime[1:min(which(cs>max(cs)-tol))] 
  if(plot == TRUE) plotTmh(Vtime, EIP)
  Vtime
}

plotTmh = function(Tmh, EIP){
  ix = 1:length(Tmh)
  plot(ix, Tmh, type ="n", 
       xlab = "Day", ylab = expression(R[mh](t)), main = "Temporal Dispersion of Infective Bites")
  vix = ix[-c(1:(EIP-1))]
  lines(vix, Tmh[vix])
  scl = max(Tmh)
  segments(EIP, 0.2*scl, EIP, scl, lty = 2)
  text(EIP, .1*scl, "EIP")
}

HTC and its temporal dispersion

We also need the temporal dispersion of infectiousness of humans. Here it is scaled arbitrarily to one:

makeDtime = function(D=38, tol = 0.00001, plot=FALSE){ 
  Dtime = c(rep(0, 17), dgamma(1:730, 2, .03))
  Dt = D*Dtime/sum(Dtime)
  ix = 1:max(which(cumsum(Dt)<D*(1-tol)))
  Dt = Dt[ix]
  Dt = Dt*D/sum(Dt)
  if(plot==TRUE)
    plot(ix, Dt[ix], type = "l", ylab = expression(D(t)), main = "HTC", xlab = "Time (Days)")
  return(Dt)
}
Dt1 = makeDtime(tol=0.0001, plot=TRUE)

Thm

\[\begin{equation} {\cal T}_{H\rightarrow M}(t,t_1) = \begin{array}{cl} 0 & \mbox{if } t<t_1\\ fqM(t)c(a) &\mbox{if } t>t_1 + \tau \end{array} \end{equation}\]

# ftMozy is a canonical seasonal mosquito pattern 
makeThm = function(t, Dt, ftMozypar, fq=0.3, plot=FALSE){
  ix = 1:length(Dt) 
  Thm = fq*Dt*ftMozy(t + ix, ftMozypar) 
  ftMozyt = ftMozy(t+ix, ftMozypar)
  if(plot==TRUE){
    plot(Thm, type = "l", ylab = expression(R[mh]), xlab = "Time (Days)")
    lines(ftMozyt*max(Thm)/max(ftMozyt), col = "blue")
  } 
  return(Thm)
}

Serial Interval

makeSerial = function(Tmh, Dt, plot=FALSE){
  mxT = length(Tmh) + length(Dt) +1 
  Serial = c(1:mxT)*0
  ix = 1:length(Tmh)
  ixx = 1:length(Dt)

  for(t in ixx) Serial[t+ix] = Serial[t+ix] + Tmh*Dt[t]
  Serial = Serial/sum(Serial)
  if (plot == TRUE){
    plot(Serial/max(Serial), type = "l", main = "", ylab = "Scaled Value", xlab = "Time (Days)", col = "purple", lwd=2)
    lines(Dt/max(Dt), col = "darkblue")
    lines(Tmh/max(Tmh), col = "darkred")
  }
  Serial
}
serial = makeSerial(Tmh1, Dt1, plot=TRUE)

removeLeadingZeros=function(Rt){
  if(Rt[1,2]>0) return(Rt)
  ix = which(Rt[,2]==0)
  ixx = min(which(diff(ix)>1)) 
  Rt[-c(1:ixx),]
} 

removeTrailingZeros = function(Rt){
  L = length(Rt[,1])
  if(Rt[L,2]>0) return(Rt) 
  ix = which(Rt[,2]==0)
  ixx = which(diff(ix)>1) 
  if(length(ixx)==0 & max(ix)==L){
    Rt_new = Rt[-ix,]
  } else { 
    rmix = c(ix[max(ixx)]+2:L)
    Rt_new = Rt[-rmix,]
  }
  return(Rt_new)
}

rmZeros = function(Rt){
  Rt = removeLeadingZeros(Rt) 
  Rt = removeTrailingZeros(Rt) 
  return (Rt)
}

One Generation

For a human case that started on some day, when would the next cases arise? This is the question we must take up with the temporal next-generation operator. Given the dispersion in mosquitoes and humans, the temporal dispersion of \(R_0\) looks like this:

calR2R = function(ftMozypar, Tmh, Dt, fq=0.3, clr="black", plot=FALSE){
  M = mean(ftMozy(1:365, ftMozypar))
  #print("R0 is approximately:") 
  #print(fq*M*sum(Dt)*sum(Tmh))
  ftMozyp = parftMozy.M(M)
  Thm = makeThm(0, Dt, ftMozyp, fq)
  mxT = length(Tmh) + length(Thm) +1 
  Rtime = c(1:mxT)*0
  ix = 1:length(Tmh)
  ixx = 1:length(Thm)

  #This does the convolution 
  for(i in ixx){
    Rtime[i+ix] = Rtime[i+ix] + Tmh*Thm[i]
  } 
  sum(Rtime)
}
calR2R(ftMozy3p, Tmh1, Dt1)
ftMozy3p1$M = ftMozy3p$M/474 
calR2R(ftMozy3p1, Tmh1, Dt1)
calRtime = function(t, Tmh, Dt, ftMozypar, fq=0.3, clr="black", plot=FALSE){
  Thm = makeThm(t, Dt, ftMozypar, fq)
  mxT = length(Tmh) + length(Thm) +1 
  Rtime = c(1:mxT)*0
  ix = 1:length(Tmh)
  ixx = 1:length(Thm)

  #This does the convolution 
  for(i in ixx){
    Rtime[i+ix] = Rtime[i+ix] + Tmh*Thm[i]
  } 
  tt = t + c(1:mxT) 
  Rtobj = cbind(tt, Rtime) 
  rmZeros(Rtobj)
}
Rt2 = calRtime(0, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozy3p)
Rt1 = calRtime(180, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozy3p)
Rt3 = calRtime(270, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozy3p)
yx =max(Rt2[,2], Rt1[,2], Rt3[,2]) 
xx =max(Rt2[,1], Rt1[,1], Rt3[,1]) 
tt = 1:xx
ftMozyt = ftMozy(tt, ftMozy3p)

lines(Rt1, col = "red")
lines(Rt2, col = "blue")
lines(Rt3, col = "green")

Multiple Generations

nextGen = function(thisGen, Tmh, Dt, ftMozypar, fq=0.3){
  
  t_thisGen = thisGen[,1]
  Rt_thisGen = thisGen[,2]
  t0 = min(t_thisGen)
  tX_thisGen = max(t_thisGen)
  
  ti = tX_thisGen  
  Rt = calRtime(ti, Tmh, Dt, ftMozypar)
  tX = max(Rt[,1])*2
  
  tt = t0:tX
  nextGen = 0*tt
  for(ti in t_thisGen){
    i = ti-t0+1
    Rt = calRtime(ti, Tmh, Dt, ftMozypar)
    ix = Rt[,1]-t0
    nextGen[ix] = nextGen[ix] + Rt[,2]*Rt_thisGen[i]
  }
  
  Rtobj = cbind(tt, nextGen)
  rmZeros(Rtobj)
}
ftMozyp = ftMozy3p
Rt.1 = calRtime(0, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozyp)
Rt.2 = nextGen(Rt.1, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozyp, fq=0.3)

Rt.3 = nextGen(Rt.2, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozyp, fq=0.3)
Rt.4 = nextGen(Rt.3, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozyp, fq=0.3)
Rt.5 = nextGen(Rt.4, Tmh1, Dt1, ftMozyp, fq=0.3)
Rt.x = Rt.5

makeNGens = function(t, Tmh, Dt, ftMozyp, fq=0.3, N=10){
  gens = list()
  Rt = calRtime(t, Tmh, Dt, ftMozyp, fq)
  gens[[1]] = Rt
  for(i in 1:N){
    Rt=nextGen(Rt, Tmh, Dt, ftMozyp, fq)
    gens[[i+1]] = Rt
  }
  return(gens)
}
plotGens = function(gens, Fclr, offset=0, mx=NULL){
  L = length(gens)
  clr = Fclr(L)
  
  if(is.null(mx)) {
    xl = c(min(gens[[1]][,1]), max(gens[[L]][,1])) 
  } else {
    xl = c(min(gens[[1]][,1]), mx) 
  }
  tt = c(1:max(gens[[L]][,1]))/365
  
  yx = 0
  for(i in 1:L) yx = max(yx,gens[[i]][,2])
  
  yl = c(0, yx)
  plot(gens[[1]], xlim = xl, ylim = yl, type = "n", ylab = expression(R[0](t)), xlab = "Time (Years)", lwd=2, xaxt = "n")
  axis(1, c(0:10)*365, c(0:10)) 
  for(i in 1:L){
     ixx = which(gens[[i]][,2]>.00001*max(gens[[i]][,2]))
     #lines(gens[[i]], col=clr[i], lty = (i+2)%%3+1, lwd=2)
     #lines(gens[[i]], col=clr[i], lty = i%%4+1)
     lines(gens[[i]][ixx,1], gens[[i]][ixx,2]+i*offset, col=clr[i])
  }
}

FclrsA = function(N,X=4){
  c1 = rev(viridis(N+X, option = "viridis"))[1:N+X]
  c2 = viridis(N+X, option = "magma")[1:N+X]
  c3 = rev(viridis(N+X, option = "rocket"))[1:N+X] 
  as.vector(as.matrix(rbind(c1,c2,c3)))
}

seasonalGens = function(gens){
  L = length(gens)
  getRbyDay=function(t, Rt){
    ty = Rt[,1]%%365+1
    ix=which(ty==t)
    sum(Rt[ix,2]) 
  }
  seasonMatrix = matrix(0, L, 365) 
  
  for(i in 1:L)
     seasonMatrix[i,] = sapply(1:365, getRbyDay, gens[[i]])
  return(seasonMatrix)
}

seasonalGens(gens)->seasMatrix
plotSeasMatrix = function(seasMatrix, N, Fclr, t0=NULL){
  clr1 = viridis(10)[2]
  clr2 = viridis(10)[8]
  L = dim(seasMatrix)[1]
  clrs = Fclr(L)
  yl = c(0, max(seasMatrix)) 
  yx = max(seasMatrix)
  par(mar = c(1,5,1,2))
  plot(1:365, seasMatrix[1,], type = "l", ylim = yl, col = clr1, lwd=2,  xaxt="n", xlab = "", ylab = expression(R[i](d)))
  lines(1:365, seasMatrix[2,], col=clr2) 
  text(50, yx*.85, "Gen 1", col = clr1)
  text(50, yx*.7, "Gen 2", col = clr2)
  if(!is.null(t0)) segments(t0%%365+1, 0, t0%%365+1, yl[2], col = grey(0.3))
  for(i in 1:(N-2)){
    j = 2*i+1 
    plot(1:365, seasMatrix[j,], type = "l", ylim = yl, col = clr1, lwd=2, xaxt="n", xlab = "", ylab = expression(R[i](d)))
    lines(1:365, seasMatrix[j+1,], col=clr2) 
    lines(1:365, seasMatrix[j-1,], col=grey(0.3), lty=2) 
    text(50, yx*.85, paste("Gen ", j), col = clr1)
    text(50, yx*.7, paste("Gen ", j+1), col = clr2)
  }
  par(mar = c(2,5,0,2))
  plot(1:365, seasMatrix[N,], type = "l", ylim = yl, col = clrs[i], xaxt="n",  xlab="Day of Year", ylab = expression(R[i](d)))
  for (i in (j+1):(L-1)) 
    lines(1:365, seasMatrix[i,], ylim = yl, col = clrs[i])
  lines(1:365, seasMatrix[L,], ylim = yl, col = "black", lwd=2)
  
#  plot(1:365, seasMatrix[L,], type = "l", ylim = yl, col = "black", lwd=2, xlab="Day of Year, d", ylab = expression(R[i](d)))
}

contourGens = function(gens){
  
  L = length(gens)
  t0 = min(gens[[1]][,1])
  tX = max(gens[[L]][,1])
  genMatrix = matrix(0, L, tX-t0+1) 
  
  for(i in 1:L){
    tt = gens[[i]][,1]
    R  = gens[[i]][,2]
    ix = tt-t0+1 
    genMatrix[i,ix]=R
  }

  return(genMatrix)
}
